    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Eurya sericea improperly include experiencing nausea, cause diarrhea, and induce nausea, which are likely due to the presence of toxic compounds such as flavonoids and phenolic acids, particularly gallic acid and ellagic acid. These compounds can have gastroenteric irritant properties, causing stomach upset, nausea, and diarrhea. Prolonged exposure to these compounds can lead to more severe gastrointestinal symptoms. The improper use of Eurya sericea may also result in nausea, as the body attempts to eliminate the toxic substances. This can lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalances if left unaddressed.",
    "uses": "Eurya sericea has been traditionally used in various cultures for its medicinal properties. It is reported to have anti-inflammatory and antibacterial properties, which may contribute to its potential health benefits. The plant is sometimes used in traditional medicine to treat various ailments, including fever and skin conditions. However, more research is needed to confirm its effectiveness and safety. Further studies are required to fully understand the medicinal uses of Eurya sericea.",
    "taxonomy": "Eurya sericea is classified in the family Pentaphylacaceae. This family is a part of the order Ericales, which is a large and diverse group of flowering plants. Eurya sericea is also classified in the genus Eurya, which is native to tropical and subtropical regions of Asia. The Pentaphylacaceae family is closely related to the Theaceae and Ebenaceae families. The classification of Eurya sericea is based on its unique characteristics, such as its small, fragrant flowers and its hairy, deciduous leaves.",
    "benefits": "Eurya sericea is reported to have various health benefits, including antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. It is used in traditional medicine to treat various ailments such as fever, rheumatism, and digestive issues. The plant's leaves and stems are believed to have a soothing effect on the skin, reducing inflammation and promoting wound healing. Eurya sericea's antiseptic properties are also thought to help prevent infections and promote the healing of cuts and wounds. Additionally, it may have anti-cancer properties due to its high content of flavonoids and phenolic acids.",
    "parts": "Eurya sericea. The medicinal parts of Eurya sericea, commonly known as the Sericeous Eurya, are its leaves and roots. Traditionally, they have been used in herbal medicine to treat various ailments, including fever and skin conditions. The leaves are typically harvested when the plant is in full growth, and the roots are dug up when the plant is mature. In some Asian cultures, Eurya sericea is valued for its potential anti-inflammatory properties.",
    "intro": "Eurya sericea is a plant species within the family Theaceae, commonly known as the tea family, which is native to the tropical regions of Asia. Eurya sericea is valued for its medicinal properties, with reported health benefits including anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant effects, which may aid in reducing pain, fighting infections, and protecting against oxidative stress. The bioactive constituents of Eurya sericea include flavonoids, triterpenoids, and phenolic acids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional medicine, Eurya sericea is often used to prepare teas, infusions, and decoctions, which are used to treat various health conditions, including fever, cough, and digestive issues."
